# Order Validation Framework

## Overview

Order validation ensures that purchase orders meet operational, financial, and compliance requirements before they enter fulfillment workflows.

This stage acts as a quality checkpoint designed to detect errors before orders impact inventory allocation, shipment execution, or billing accuracy.

---

## Validation Objectives

The primary objectives of order validation include:

• ensuring SKU accuracy  
• verifying pricing agreements  
• confirming order quantities  
• validating retailer compliance requirements  
• confirming inventory availability  

Effective validation prevents operational disruptions later in the order lifecycle.

---

## Typical Validation Checks

Order validation typically includes several operational checkpoints.

### Product Validation

Operations teams verify that product identifiers are valid and available.

Examples include:

• SKU validation  
• product catalog verification  
• discontinued product detection

### Pricing Validation

Pricing must match the negotiated retailer agreement.

Examples include:

• wholesale pricing confirmation  
• promotional pricing checks  
• contract pricing validation

### Quantity Validation

Orders must align with operational constraints.

Examples include:

• minimum order quantities  
• case pack validation  
• allocation limits

### Compliance Validation

Retailers often have specific requirements for shipments.

Examples include:

• routing guide compliance  
• packaging requirements  
• labeling rules

---

## Operational Benefits

Strong validation processes help organizations:

• reduce fulfillment errors  
• avoid retailer penalties and chargebacks  
• prevent inventory allocation conflicts  
• maintain accurate financial records

---

## Validation Ownership

Order validation is typically managed by:

• order operations teams  
• sales operations teams  
• system automation through ERP rules  

Automation can assist validation but human oversight remains important for exception management.
